WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.400
Today I just want to show people how to get started making a basic Shiny app and just

00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:12.040
understanding the basic concepts. In order to do that, we can just start from the website.

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:19.400
This is the Shiny for Python website. It's shiny.rstudio.com.py. I know that might be

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:24.600
really little in the browser, but we'll post a link for that. And the easiest way to get

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:29.120
started just working in code is just click on examples. All right, and that will take

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:37.000
you to this website, shinylive.io, where you can just work on your code here. You

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.639
can look at the examples, edit the code, and run the apps. This is one of the most exciting

00:00:41.639 --> 00:00:48.040
things, I think, is that you can use Shiny without having to install anything, without

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:53.799
having to install even Python on your system. You can just get in here and start working

00:00:53.799 --> 00:00:59.080
right away. And then, you know, as you develop an app that becomes more sophisticated, you

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:07.279
can work in a regular Python installation. But to get started, this is a great way to

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:12.080
do it. Okay, so let's take a look at this example app. There's a whole bunch of different

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:17.599
examples over here, but by default, it just starts on this page. And to understand how

00:01:17.599 --> 00:01:22.440
a Shiny application is built, there's two main components. There's the UI, which is

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:25.360
the part that's displayed in the web browser. This is a web page that's displayed in the

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:31.839
web browser over here. And then there's the server logic. And this is Python code that

00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:40.400
gets executed when somebody connects to this application. It executes this code once, and

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:50.000
then it will re-execute reactive functions in response to user input. So there's a UI

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.440
over here. There's the server code here. And then that stuff gets put together into

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:02.120
a Shiny app object over here. And so we're calling this app object app, which is that's

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:08.600
what you have to call it for this all to work. Let's take a look at the UI. So in this case,

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:15.320
we have input slider, which is this thing over here. And then output text verbatim.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:21.320
So this is a text output, and the verbatim means that it's printed as code with a monospace

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:32.679
font instead of being printed as normal HTML text. And as we change the slider, it causes

00:02:32.679 --> 00:02:39.000
this output to change. All right. So we've got this input and this output component,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.479
and they're wrapped up inside of something called a page fluid. Now, we don't have to

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:48.800
know the details about this right now, but for most applications at this point, we can

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:54.440
just wrap these components in a page fluid. All right. So now what's connecting them together

00:02:54.440 --> 00:03:00.960
is this server logic here. This is a function. It's called server. And as I said earlier,

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:05.600
it gets executed once when the user connects to the application. Now, there's a bunch of

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:11.440
these decorators here. This is saying we've got this thing that's an output. It's rendering

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:21.759
text. And then here we're defining the function txt, which returns a string. Now, I'm going to

00:03:21.759 --> 00:03:25.919
change some of these names just to make it a little easier to explain things. So let's say

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:40.240
we'll call this slider my slider and input my slider and text. You know, I'll call it txt

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:47.119
computation. All right. We'll put this over here as well. So I made some changes to this

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:52.399
application. I'm just going to I can click this button to rerun it. Now, it looks the same. But

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:55.839
over here, the variables should be it'll be a little easier to see how things line up.

00:03:57.199 --> 00:04:06.479
So I've got the slider input. And it's the idea of it is my slider. And then I can read it in

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:12.720
this function down here. So I can say input dot my slider. And I invoke that as a function. And

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:19.600
this this function will return the current value of the slider. And then what I'm taking what I'm

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:26.720
doing with that value is I'm putting into a string. And this function text computation,

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:34.239
it takes this string, and it's sticking it into this output text verbatim. One of the cool things

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:39.920
about Shiny is its reactive computing model. So if I move this slider, I don't have to do anything

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:47.519
extra to tell it to re execute this function, it just knows, like, hey, input my slider is changed.

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:51.920
So re execute this function, every time I do that. All right.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:58.399
Now I can do some other things to this, like I can change this label here, I can say, you know,

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:06.320
input a value here. And I can, because this is all running within the web browser,

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:10.640
Python is running in the web browser, and Shiny is running in the web browser,

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:15.200
I can just click this button here and re execute, re execute this application every time I make

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:30.959
changes to it. So it makes it really easy to try out new things.

